vent=Victor,D.J., Rfn <ref name=32BatROH />{{rp|1598}}{{efn|name=Star}}}}\n* {{Timeline-event|date=1980|event=Yenga,M., Rfn <ref name=32BatROH />{{rp|1857}}{{efn|name=Star}}}}\n{{div col end}}\n\n== Leadership ==\n<ref name=\"TRC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sabctrc.saha.org.za/reports/volume2/chapter3/subsection69.htm |title=TRC Final Report |publisher=SABC |accessdate=10 March 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141224105920/http://www.sabctrc.saha.org.za/reports/volume2/chapter3/subsection69.htm |archivedate=24 December 2014 }}</ref>\n{{Post-start|caption=32 Battalion Leadership|float=}}\n{{Post-header|post-name=Commanding Officers}}\n{{Post-member|from-date=1975|post-incumbent=Colonel [[Jan Breytenbach]]|to-date=1977}}\n{{Post-member|from-date=1977|post-incumbent=Col [[Gert Nel (soldier)|Gert Nel]]|to-date=1978}}\n{{Post-member|from-date=1978|post-incumbent=Col [[Deon Ferreira]] (''Falcon'')|to-date=1983}}\n{{Post-member|from-date=1984|post-incumbent=Col [[Eddie Viljoen]] (''Big Daddy'')|to-date=1988}}\n{{Post-member|from-date=n.d.|post-incumbent=Col [[Jock Harris]]|to-date=n.d.}}\n{{Post-member|from-date=1988|post-incumbent=Col [[Mucho Delport]]|to-date=1993}}\n{{Post-header|post-name=Regimental Sergeants Major}}\n{{Post-member|from-date=1978|post-incumbent=WO1 [[Pep Van Zyl]]|to-date=1980}}\n{{Post-member|from-date=1980|post-incumbent=WO1 [[Ickes Uekermann]]|to-date=1982}}\n{{Post-member|from-date=1983|post-incumbent=WO1 [[PW van Heerden]]|to-date=1983}}\n{{Post-member|from-date=1984|post-incumbent=WO1 [[Fanie Joubert]]|to-date=1985}}\n{{Post-member|from-date=1985|post-incumbent=WO1 [[Piet Nortje]]|to-date=1987}}\n{{Post-member|from-date=1988|post-incumbent=WO1 [[Tallies Botha]]|to-date=1991}}\n{{Post-member|from-date=1992|post-incumbent=WO1 [[Tienie Geldenhuys]]|to-date=1993}}\n{{Post-end}}\n\n== Insignia ==\n===Dress Insignia===\n\n[[File:SADF era 32 Battalion insignia.jpg|thumb|center|900px|SADF era 32 Battalion insignia]]\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|South Africa}}\n* [[32 Battalion (book)|''32 Battalion'' (book)]] (by Piet Nortje, 2004)\n* [[South African Special Forces Brigade]] (\"Recces\")\n* [[List of operations of the South African Border War]]\n* [[Operation Savannah (Angola)|Operation Savannah]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071011203854/http://www.32battalion.net/ Official Website of the 32Bn VA]\n* [http://flecha.co.uk/ \"The Terrible Ones\"]\n* [http://www.recce.co.za/ South African Special Forces League]\n* [http://www.justdone.co.za/roh/main.php?page=List_People&UnitAbv=32Bat SA Roll of Honour Database]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20081223112226/http://justdone.co.za/shop/product.php?id_product=318 To the Bush and Back by Nico van der Walt]\n\n{{South African Border War}}\n{{SA Army Units}}\n\n[[Category:Expatriate units and formations]]\n[[Category:Infantry battalions of South Africa]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations disestablished in 1993]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 1975]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations of South Africa in the Border War]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations of the Cold War]]\n[[Category:Organisations associated with apartheid]]\n", "text_old": "{{redirect|The Terrible Ones|the novel in the Nick Carter-Killmaster series|The Terrible Ones (novel)}}\n{{Use South African English|date=January 2015}}\n<!-- Image with unknown copyright status removed: [[Image:32a.jpg|right|thumb|32Bn Emblem]] -->\n{{Infobox military unit\n|unit_name= 32 Battalion\n| image =SADF 32 Battalion SSI.svg\n| image_size = 150\n|caption = 32 Battalion emblem\n|dates= 1975 \u2013 26 March 1993\n|country= {{flag|South Africa|1928}}\n|allegiance=\n|branch= {{army|South Africa|1981}}\n|type= [[Light Infantry]]\n|role=\n|size=\n|command_structure=[[South African Defence Force]]\n|garrison=\n|garrison_label=\n|nickname= ''Os Terr\u00edveis'' ({{Lang-en|The Terrible Ones\"}})\n|patron=\n|motto=''Proelio Procusi'' ({{Lang-en|\"Forged in Battle\"}})\n|colors=\n|colors_label=\n|march=\n|mascot=\n|equipment=\n|equipment_label=\n|battles= [[South African Border War]]\n|anniversaries=\n|decorations=\n|battle_honours=\n|commander1=Colonel [[Jan Breytenbach]]\n|commander1_label=Founder\n|commander2={{plainlist|* Col [[Gert Nel (soldier)|Gert Nel]]* Col [[Deon Ferreira]] (''Falcon'')* Col [[Eddie Viljoen]] (''Big Daddy'')}}\n|commander2_label=Subsequent commanders\n|commander3=\n|commander3_label=Dates?\n|notable_commanders=\n<!-- Insignia -->\n| identification_symbol =[[File:SADF 32 Battalion Flag.svg|border|100px]]\n| identification_symbol_label =Battalion flag\n|slogan_structure=\n}}\n'''32 Battalion''' (sometimes nicknamed ''[[African Buffalo|Buffalo]] Battalion'' or {{lang-pt|Os Terr\u00edveis}} for ''The Terrible Ones'') was a [[light infantry]] [[battalion]] of the [[South African Army]] founded in 1975, composed of black and white [[Officer (military)|commissioned]] and [[enlisted]] personnel. It was disbanded on 26&nbsp;March 1993.<ref name=32bnBook>{{cite book|last=Nortje|first=Piet|title=32 Battalion |publisher=Zebra Press|year=2003|isbn=978-1-86872-914-2}}</ref>{{rp|280}}\n\n== History ==\n===Military refugees===\nAfter the victory of the ''Movimento Popular de Liberta\u00e7\u00e3o de Angola'' ([[MPLA]]) in the [[Angolan War of Independence]] in 1975, many troops of its main rival, the ''Frente Nacional de Liberta\u00e7\u00e3o de Angola'' ([[National Liberation Front of Angola]], FNLA), found refuge in the then [[South Africa]]n-controlled [[South West Africa]].<ref name=\"DeLancey-1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.etext.org/Politics/AlternativeOrange/2/v2n2_misa.html |title=\u2026meanwhile, in South Africa, the bloody capitalist-apartheid regime remains\u2026 |last=De Lancey |first=Blaine |date=November 1992 |publisher=Syracuse University |accessdate=2015-12-10 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080201115234/http://www.etext.org/Politics/AlternativeOrange/2/v2n2_misa.html |archivedate=February 1, 2008 }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Figure32Battalion.jpg|thumb|200px|left|32 Battalion uniforms. Members of the unit often impersonated Angolan security forces.]]\n\n===Formation of Bravo Group===\nFrom these troops, Colonel [[Jan Breytenbach]] together with [[Commandant#South Africa|Commandant]] Sybie van der Spuy formed a unit that was initially known as Bravo Group but later renamed 32&nbsp;Battalion. Initially, Bravo Group consisted of two infantry companies, a mortar [[platoon]], an anti-tank section and a [[machine gun]] platoon, but 32&nbsp;Battalion was finally expanded to seven infantry companies, a reconnaissance wing, and a support company consisting of 81&nbsp;mm mortar, anti-tank and machine gun sections.\n\n[[File:32 Battalion Structure.jpg|900px|32 Battalion Structure]]\n\n===Redeployed as the SADF===\nUnlike other [[South African Defence Forces]] (SADF) units, 32&nbsp;Battalion was mainly deployed in southern [[Angola]], acting as a buffer between the SADF's regular forces and its socialist enemies. The unit was also used to assist the [[anti-communist]] movement of the National Union for the Total Independence of Angola ([[UNITA]]). Although it was mainly used as a counter-insurgency force it was eventually also used as a semi-conventional force, especially during the later phases of the war&nbsp;\u2013 particularly at the [[Battle of Cuito Cuanavale]].\n\nThe battalion consisted of around 700 riflemen and NCOs ([[non-commissioned officer]]s) (mostly Angolan nationals associated with the former FNLA or the Portuguese Army) and mainly South African officers, although commissioned military personnel from countries such as [[Australia]], [[Rhodesia]], [[Portugal]] and the [[United States]] were active with the battalion, especially in its early stages.  As time progressed a number of SNCOs (senior non-commissioned officers&nbsp;\u2013 sergeants and above), distinguished themselves and were commissioned.<ref>[[International Defence and Aid Fund]], January 1982</ref>\n\nAt the end of its era in [[Namibia]], the unit had developed into a conventional battle group. Apart from the infantry companies and the recce company, the battalion was strengthened by a battery of {{convert|120|mm|in|abbr=on}} mortars, a squadron of [[Ratel IFV|Ratel]] ZT-3 and {{convert|90|mm|in|abbr=on}} tank destroyers and a troop of {{convert|20|mm|in|abbr=on}} anti-aircraft guns mounted on [[Buffel]] infantry vehicles. Although the main bulk of the battalion was based at Buffalo on the banks of the [[Okavango River]], the HQ was in [[Rundu]], {{convert|200|km|mi|abbr=on}} to the west{{Citation needed|date=September 2011}}.\n\n===Namibian independence===\nAfter [[Namibian independence]] in 1989-1990, the unit was withdrawn to South Africa where it was further used in a [[counter-insurgency]] role on South Africa's borders and later also in [[townships]].\n\n===Phola Park Incident===\nOn 8&nbsp;April 1992 members of 32&nbsp;Battalion were involved in an incident in Phola Park, [[Gauteng]] where members of the public were shot and killed.<ref name=\"Goldstone-Phola\">{{cite web|url=http://hurisa.org.za/wp-content/uploads/2009/11/Goldstone-Booklet.pdf|title=An interim report on the conduct of members of 32 Battalion at Phola Park on 8 April 1992|date=1992-06-10|work=Goldstone Commission of Inquiry Regarding the prevention of Public Violence and Intimidation|publisher=Human Rights Institute of South Africa|accessdate=2008-11-27}}</ref> The incident drew widespread criticism, specifically from the [[African National Congress]] (ANC)<ref name=\"ANC-Phola\">{{cite web|url=http://www.anc.org.za/ancdocs/pr/1992/pr0410a.html |title=Statement on Battalion 32's rampage through Phola Park |date=1992-04-10 |publisher=Department of Information and Publicity |accessdate=2008-11-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080708193835/http://www.anc.org.za/ancdocs/pr/1992/pr0410a.html |archivedate=July 8, 2008 }}</ref> and prompted the Minister of Defence to request an investigation by the [[Richard Goldstone|Goldstone]] Commission.\n\n===Disbandment===\nAs one of the results of the negotiations between the [[National Party (South Africa)|National Party]] and the ANC, the unit was disbanded in March 1993. After the battalion was disbanded, the remaining members of the unit were transferred to other SADF-units such as the Parachute and Mechanised Battalions as well as the ''Recces''. It was also decided to reactivate 2-SAI at Pomfret which enabled about a quarter of the troops to return to Pomfret as members of the new 2-SAI. However, when 2-SAI was moved to Zeerust in 1999, many of them decided to rather stay behind at Pomfret and handed in their resignations.  In 2008 there still remained about a quarter of the original 1,000 ''three-two'' families at Pomfret, eking out mainly a hand-to-mouth existence.\n\nMany members of the unit later helped to found or joined private military companies such as [[Executive Outcomes]] and [[Sandline International]], which fought on the side of the Angolan government against UNITA.\n[[File:SADF 32 Battalion commemorative medallion.jpg|thumb|center|200px|SADF 32 Battalion commemorative medallion]]\n\n===Equatorial Guinea coup===\nSome of the participants in the alleged [[2004 Equatorial Guinea coup d'\u00e9tat attempt]] were former members of 32&nbsp;Battalion.<ref name=\"IOL-coup\">{{cite web|url=http://www.iol.co.za/index.php?set_id=1&click_id=13&art_id=ct20040314091038442P430771|title=Koevoet, 32 battalion and the coup plot...|last=Terblanche|first=Christelle|author2=Peter Fabricus|date=2004-03-14|publisher=Independent Online|accessdate=2008-10-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/ac2/wp-dyn/A48639-2004Sep24?language=printer|title=African Coup Plot Leaves Kin Bereft|last=Timberg|first=Craig  |date=2004-09-25|publisher=Washington Post Foreign Service|accessdate=2008-12-01}}</ref> Because they were arrested in [[Zimbabwe]], it is not clear whether any of those arrested had full knowledge of their final destination or the alleged coup d'\u00e9tat.<ref>''Once Upon a Coup'', [[PBS]] Documentary, August 2009, https://www.pbs.org/wnet/wideangle/episodes/once-upon-a-coup/full-episode/?p=5496</ref>\n\n== Decorations ==\nThe battalion was one of the most decorated units during the [[South African Border War]], with a total of 13 [[Honoris Crux (1975)|Honoris Crux]] medals for bravery awarded to its members, second only to the [[South African Special Forces Brigade]], whose members were awarded 46 Honoris Crux medals during the same period.\n\n{{hidden begin\n|title = [[Image:Ribbon - Honoris Crux (1975).gif|48px]] [[Image:HC2lint.gif|48px]] List of 32 Battalion recipients of the [[Honoris Crux (1975)|Honoris Crux]]<ref name=32bnBook />{{rp|85\u201388}}\n|titlestyle  = text-align:left;background:#b0c4de;height:20px;padding:1px;\n|bodystyle  = text-align:left;\n}}\n{{main|Honoris Crux (1975)}}\n* Lieutenant Connie van Wyk\n* Sergeant [[Danny Roxo]]\n* Warrant Officer 2 Willy Ward\n* Major [[Eddie Viljoen]]\n* Lance Corporal Feliciano Costa\n* Corporal Eduardo Jo\u00e3o\n* Second Lieutenant Petrus Nel\n* Corporal Victor Dracula\n* Rifleman Bernardo Domingos\n* Major Hannes Nortmann\n* Sergeant Rihan Rupping\n* Captain Petrus van Zyl&nbsp;\u2013 [[Operation Modular]]\n* Lieutenant Tobias de Vos&nbsp;\u2013 Operation Modular\n{{hidden end}}\n\n==In fiction==\nIn the film ''[[Blood Diamond (film)|Blood Diamond]]'', [[Leonardo DiCaprio]]'s [[White people in Zimbabwe|Rhodesian]] character \"Danny Archer\" was a former member of 32&nbsp;Battalion.\n\n==Roll of Honour==\n[[File:32 Battalion Tree of Honour.jpg|thumb|250px|right|32 Battalion Tree of Honour]]\n{{div col|colwidth=18em}}\n* {{Timeline-event|date=1980|event=Alberto,R., Rfn<ref name=32BatROH>{{cite web|last1=Dovey|first1=John|title=SA Roll of Honour: 32 (Buffalo) Battali